    <!-- <p>It's traditional to use the variable <m>x</m> to represent numbers on the left-right axis, so we call that axis the <term><m>x</m>-axis</term>.<index><main><m>x</m>-axis</main></index> For similar reasons we call the down-up axis the <term><m>y</m>-axis</term>.<index><main><m>y</m>-axis</main></index> The point <m>(0,0)</m> is where the two axes meet, and we call it the <term>origin</term>.<index><main>origin</main></index> We use an <term>ordered pair</term>, like <m>(2,3)</m>, to represent the location of a point.<index><main>ordered pair</main></index> We are ready for a formal definition of the <term>Cartesian Coordinate System</term> and several associated vocabulary terms.</p> -->
    <p>Traditionally, the variable <m>x</m> represents numbers on the horizontal axis, so it is called the <term><m>x</m>-axis</term>.<index><main><m>x</m>-axis</main></index> The variable <m>y</m> represents numbers on the vertical axis, so it is called the <term><m>y</m>-axis</term>.<index><main><m>y</m>-axis</main></index> The axes meet at the point <m>(0,0)</m>, which is called the <term>origin</term>.<index><main>origin</main></index> Every point in the plane is represented by an <term>ordered pair</term>, <m>(x,y)</m>.<index><main>ordered pair</main></index></p>

